Rivers State Governor,  Nyesom Wike has declared that he will not impose a successor on the people of the state after the expiration of his second term in 2023. Wike, who made the declaration yesterday during a solidarity visit by the Orashi Region of Rivers State to the Government House, Port Harcourt, said power can never be extended as a  gift to any group. The governor said: “For the position of governorship, if you have the capacity,  come out and contest. Nobody zoned governorship to me, I struggled for it. “I will not impose anybody on Rivers people as Governor in 2023. I will not do it. I don’t even have that power, not to talk of giving it out. You cannot give what you don’t have. To be governor of Rivers State, you must have the capacity to deliver.” He warned against politics of bitterness, which he said has denied several Rivers communities access to developmental projects. Wike said: “Don’t allow anyone to sow seeds of discord among you. Politics should not divide us. Politics of bitterness does not make sense. “All of us must not be in one political party. But you must support yourselves to attract projects to your area,” he said. The governor urged the people of Orashi to remain steadfast in their march towards development.  He advised them not to be intimidated as they seek development. Wike, who called on communities to take steps to protect ongoing government projects, regretted that in Ahoada East and Ahoada West local government areas, some youths disrupted execution of projects through vandalism and kidnapping. The governor particularly decried the invasion of Western Ahoada County Grammar School, the Zonal Hospital Ahoada and Government Secondary School, Okarki by the people of the area. Earlier in his speech, former deputy speaker of the House of Representatives,  Rt Hon Chibodum Nwuche thanked the Rivers State Governor for siting key projects in Ekpeye land. Nwuche described Wike as a beacon of hope, who plays politics of inclusiveness.